That is a very insightful question. The short answer is yes, but it depends on the "dialect" of Data Engineering you are speaking.

What we've built follows the Lakehouse / Databricks standard, but here is how major tech companies vary their naming:

1. 
inbound/ vs landing/ vs raw/

    What we used: inbound/
    Databricks Standard: raw/
    AWS/GCP Standard: landing/ or staging/
    Why? Use landing or inbound if the data is "dropping in" from an external partner. Use raw if it's the 1st tier of your internal medallion architecture.

2. 
delta/ vs bronze/silver/gold
What we used: delta/bronze/ and delta/silver/
Industry Standard: Usually, people skip the word delta in the folder name and just go straight to:
    mnt/datalake/bronze/
    mnt/datalake/silver/
Why? Since Delta is the format, many engineers prefer naming the folder after the Content Tier (Bronze/Silver) rather than the Technology (Delta).
Pro Tip: If your company uses multiple formats (some Avro, some Parquet, some Delta), then naming the folder delta/ is actually a best practice because it warns other engineers: "Hey, don't try to read this with a standard Parquet reader, it's a Delta table!"

3. checkpoints/
Standard? 100% Yes.
This is the "Universal Law." Whether you use Spark, Flink, or Kafka Streams, the folder where the engine saves its state is almost universally named checkpoints.
🎓 Naming "Translation" Table (For Interviews)
If you're in an interview, you can sound like a pro by saying: "In our lab, we used a Medallion Pattern with an Explicit Technology Prefix."

*Common Term*	  *Industry Alternative*	      *When to use it?*
Inbound	          Landing / Staging	              When data is "pushing" into your system.
Delta	          Lakehouse / Analytics	          When you want to highlight the ACID capability.
Bronze	          Raw / L0	                      When data is un-typed and un-cleaned.
Silver	          Refined / Clean / L1	          When data is business-ready and physics-valid.
Checkpoint	      Offsets / State	              Purely for engine recovery logic.

